Medicare Synthetic Public Use Files

2017-02-17

The following is an exploration of the Medicare synthetic PUF Sample 1. You can learn more about Medicare data here.

At this point, I’ll just read the data and select the columns that interest me:

library(tidyverse)
library(readr)

synpuf <- 
  feather::read_feather("cache/carclaimsa.feather") %>% 
  select(DESYNPUF_ID, ICD9_DGNS_CD_1, ICD9_DGNS_CD_2)

synpuf <- 
  bind_rows(synpuf %>% select(ID = DESYNPUF_ID, icd9 = ICD9_DGNS_CD_1), 
            synpuf %>% select(ID = DESYNPUF_ID, icd9 = ICD9_DGNS_CD_2))

I specified a default column character because sometimes ICD9 codes are converted to integers (defaults are set by some first number of rows, and this doesn’t generally include the “V” or “E” codes).

Let’s see what we’ve got:

glimpse(synpuf)
## Observations: 4,745,914
## Variables: 2
## $ ID   <chr> "00000B48BCF4AD29", "00000B48BCF4AD29", "00000B48BCF4AD29...
## $ icd9 <chr> "7061", "9561", "8241", "V676", "5765", "73320", "24290",...

Looking at the codebook for this data, the difference between ICD9_DGNS_CD_[1:8] and LINE_ICD9_DGNS_CD_[1:13] is that

ICD9_DGNS_CD_[1:8] (CLAIM DIAGNOSIS CODE 1 – CLAIM DIAGNOSIS CODE 8) is defined as:

The diagnosis code identifying the beneficiary's principal or other diagnosis (including E code). NOTE: 
Prior to Version H, the principal diagnosis code was not stored with the 'OTHER' diagnosis codes. During 
the Version H conversion the CLM_PRNCPAL_DGNS_CD was added as the first occurrence. 
NOTE1: Effective with Version 'J', this field has been expanded from 5 bytes to 7 bytes to accommodate 
the future implementation of ICD
–10. 
NOTE2: Effective with Version 'J', the diagnosis E codes are stored in a separate trailer 
(CLM_DGNS_E_GRP).
Note:
These variables were imputed/suppressed/coarsened as part of disclosure treatment.  Analyses 
using these variables should be interpreted with caution.  Analytic inferences to the Medicare population 
should not be made when using these variables

and the LINE_ICD9_DGNS_CD_[1:13] (LINE DIAGNOSIS CODE 1 – LINE DIAGNOSIS CODE 13) is defined as:

The code indicating the diagnosis supporting this line item procedure/service on the noninstitutional
claim.
Note: These variables were imputed/suppressed/coarsened as part of disclosure treatment. Analyses
using these variables should be interpreted with caution. Analytic inferences to the Medicare population
should not be made when using these variables.

The [E, J] diagnosis codes appear problematic, so I’ll remove those:

# note that this introduces a blank in place of the character codes. These observations will 
# be removed upon coercion to numeric types. 

synpuf$icd9 <- gsub(x = synpuf$icd9, pattern = "[A-Z].+", replacement = NA)

As an aside, the str_extract_all appears to be slower than gsub. If I had to guess, I would say this is an issue with type conversions.

As with any new dataset, I want to see how much missingness we have:

map_dbl(synpuf, ~ length(which(is.na(.))) / length(.)) %>% 
  round(digits = 3)
##    ID  icd9 
## 0.000 0.307

Cool, not much (of the few variables) was missing.

A Networks Approach

I’ve recently become interested in probabilistic graphical models, particularly bayesian networks. bnlearn has floated across my radar several times, so I’ll be approaching learning this model using the bnlearn package. I think the data will fit, but there may very well be more munging to do.

Dimensionality reduction

The dimensionality reduction afforded by the Clinical Classification “Software” from the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality project “Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project”. For the purposes of this document, we’ll use the single-level CCS (note: this link goes to a zip file).

Here, we’ll read in the CCS tables, keeping only the variabes that interest us, and removing the alphabetical ICD codes just like above:

qcsv <- quietly(read_csv)

#skip the first line because it isn't relevant
ccs_desc <- 
  qcsv("ccs/$dxref 2015.csv", skip = 1)$result

names(ccs_desc) <- 
  gsub(x = names(ccs_desc), pattern = "\\'|\\-|CATEGORY\\ ", replacement = "")

names(ccs_desc) <- 
  gsub(x = names(ccs_desc), pattern = "\\ ", replacement = "_") %>% 
  tolower()

names(ccs_desc)
## [1] "icd9cm_code"              "ccs_category"            
## [3] "ccs_description"          "icd9cm_code_description" 
## [5] "optional_ccs_category"    "optional_ccs_description"
ccs_desc <- 
  map_df(ccs_desc, ~ gsub(x = ., pattern = "\\'", replacement = "")) %>% 
  select(icd9cm_code, ccs_description) %>% 
  mutate(icd9 = gsub(x = icd9cm_code, pattern = "[A-Z].+", replacement = NA)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(icd9)) %>%
  select(-icd9cm_code) 

glimpse(ccs_desc)
## Observations: 12,563
## Variables: 2
## $ ccs_description <chr> "No DX", "Tuberculosis", "Tuberculosis", "Tube...
## $ icd9            <chr> "     ", "01000", "01001", "01002", "01003", "...

ICD9 codes can be 3, 4, or 5 digits. The 3- and 4- digit CCS ICD9 codes all start with 0 and 00, respectively, whereas the the synthetic PUF ICD9 codes do not. We’ll have to fix that:

ccs_desc$icd9 <- 
  gsub(x = ccs_desc$icd9, pattern = "^0+", replacement = "")

glimpse(ccs_desc)
## Observations: 12,563
## Variables: 2
## $ ccs_description <chr> "No DX", "Tuberculosis", "Tuberculosis", "Tube...
## $ icd9            <chr> "     ", "1000", "1001", "1002", "1003", "1004...

And here, we’ll join the two dataframes

synpuf_ccs <-
  inner_join(synpuf, ccs_desc) %>% 
  select(-icd9)
## Joining, by = "icd9"
glimpse(synpuf_ccs)
## Observations: 1,644,636
## Variables: 2
## $ ID              <chr> "00000B48BCF4AD29", "00000B48BCF4AD29", "00000...
## $ ccs_description <chr> "Oth infectns", "Ot bone dx", "Thyroid dsor", ...

Cool! We’ve got a list of patient-diagnoses.

Next, we’ll reshape the data:

synpuf_ccs <-
  synpuf_ccs %>% filter(!is.na(ID) & !is.na(ccs_description))

synccs_wide <- 
  data.table::dcast(synpuf_ccs, formula = ID ~ ccs_description, 
                    fun.aggregate = function(x) ifelse(sum(!is.na(x)) > 0, TRUE, FALSE))
## Using 'ccs_description' as value column. Use 'value.var' to override

And we’ll clean up the casted data a little:

synccs_wide$`No DX` <- NULL
synccs_wide$Unclassified <- NULL

names(synccs_wide) <- 
  gsub(x = tolower(names(synccs_wide)), pattern = "\\s|\\-|\\/|\\;", replacement = "_")

synccs_wide$id <- NULL

At this point, we have 49,153 patients with a possible 254 different diagnoses. It’s worth noting that the whole set of International Classifications of Disease (9th revision) has something like ten thousand codes, so we’ve sacrificed precision in favor of quicker calculation according to an established ontology (the Clinical Classification System that’s put out by CMS). If it were really important, the dcast from data.table can handle all icd codes, but only about 10 million rows (on my i5 6600k with 64GB memory).

Also, solely in reshaping the data, we have lost some information. Our aggregation function reports only the presence of a diagnosis code, rather than the number of times that the patient was listed with that code.

Figuring out associations

One popular R package, arules calls a C implementation of an algorithm (apriori, by C. Borgelt) that we can use to produce our network adjacency matrix. Moreover, we can calculate relevant metrics such as odds ratios and chi-square tests of difference if we are interested in presenting this data to the traditional physician/clinical crowd. In fact, now that I think about it, it might be worth implementing a Bonferroni correction or Tukey’s Honest Significant Difference to help people make sense of the mass of results.

Here, we’ll use the arules package to produce our adjacency matrix and calculate some useful values. Note that arules considers each patient (row) a transaction and each diagnosis (column) an item.

#rm(list = ls()[-grep("synccs_wide", ls())])

library(arules)

sync_tx <- as(synccs_wide, "transactions")

rule_params <- list(supp = 0.05, conf = 0.5, 
                    maxlen = 2, target = "rules")

sync_rules <- 
  apriori(sync_tx, parameter = rule_params)
## Apriori
## 
## Parameter specification:
##  confidence minval smax arem  aval originalSupport maxtime support minlen
##         0.5    0.1    1 none FALSE            TRUE       5    0.05      1
##  maxlen target   ext
##       2  rules FALSE
## 
## Algorithmic control:
##  filter tree heap memopt load sort verbose
##     0.1 TRUE TRUE  FALSE TRUE    2    TRUE
## 
## Absolute minimum support count: 2382 
## 
## set item appearances ...[0 item(s)] done [0.00s].
## set transactions ...[206 item(s), 47659 transaction(s)] done [0.04s].
## sorting and recoding items ... [100 item(s)] done [0.02s].
## creating transaction tree ... done [0.02s].
## checking subsets of size 1 2 done [0.01s].
## writing ... [1178 rule(s)] done [0.00s].
## creating S4 object  ... done [0.01s].
qinspect <- quietly(arules::inspect)

df_rules <- data.frame(qinspect(sync_rules)$result)

df_rules <- df_rules %>% select(-2)

head(df_rules[200:205,])
## data frame with 0 columns and 6 rows

Great, we’ve got the odds ratios and chi-squared statistics for each of the itemsets. I want to point out that we are only considering diagnoses that occurred at a frequency of at least 5 per 1000. In other words, at least 2383 must have had the left-hand diagnosis for us to consider its possible associations.

Again, to make things easier, we’re limiting ourselves to only diagnosis-diagnosis associations. It is possible to consider any number of items in each set, but I have yet to experiment with visualizing hyperedges.

Before making a networks-type visualization, let’s see what kind of results we’ve got. I’ll plot odds ratio against support, representing (the odds of the left hand side divided by the odds of the right hand side) plotted against (the proportion of transactions with the left hand side item)

library(viridis)

# df_rules <-
#   df_rules %>%
#   mutate(OR = interestMeasure(sync_rules, measure = "oddsRatio", transactions = sync_tx),
#          chi_square =  interestMeasure(sync_rules, measure = "chiSquared", transactions = sync_tx))
df_rules$chi_square <- interestMeasure(sync_rules, measure = "chiSquared", transactions = sync_tx)
df_rules$OR <- interestMeasure(sync_rules, measure = "oddsRatio", transactions = sync_tx)

#test <- interestMeasure(sync_rules, measure = c("oddsRatio", "chiSquared"), transactions = sync_tx)

ggplot(df_rules, aes(support, OR, color = chi_square)) +
  geom_point(alpha = I(1/2)) +
  labs(x = "Proportion of transactions with left hand side diagnosis",
       y = "Odds ratio", title = "Odds ratios for all associations") +
  scale_color_viridis()

Network Visualization

library(network)
library(ggnetwork)

df_rules_sample <- df_rules %>% sample_n(150) %>% filter(OR < 3.8)

make_quantile <- 
  ecdf(df_rules$chi_square)

sync_net <- 
  network(x = select(df_rules_sample, lhs, rhs),
          vertex.attr = list(df_rules_sample$support, 
                             df_rules_sample$OR, 
                             make_quantile(df_rules_sample$chi_square)), 
          vertex.attrnames = c("Support", "OR", "XSquare"),
          directed = TRUE)

set.seed(123123)

#Trying out different layouts for size

 # geom_segment(aes(color = XSquare)) +

Naive Bayes

Knowing that one focus of your program is predictive modeling, here’s a naive bayes model predicting tuberculosis:

library(e1071)

tuberculosis_model <-
  naiveBayes(tuberculosis ~ ., data = synccs_wide)

head(tuberculosis_model)[[2]][205]
## $wht_blood_dx
##        wht_blood_dx
## Y            FALSE       TRUE
##   FALSE 0.95555556 0.04444444
##   TRUE  0.87397468 0.12602532

As an example, it looks like about 12.6% of people with tuberculosis also had a white blood cell diagnosis. In contrast, people without tuberculosis had white blood cell diagnoses at a rate of 4.4%. We can look through all of the diseases for interesting ones, too, if we are looking for explanatory information. Of course, we can use the conditional probabilities to make predictions regarding tuberculosis status, as well.

Future directions: While the naive bayes is cool, one of my upcoming goals is to design a bayesian network based on domain knowledge (physiology) and learn it from diagnosis data.
